AVD Definition
Azure Virtual Desktop is a desktop & application virtualization service which runs on Azure.

AVD Function
• Full Windows experience - AVD delivers a full Windows experience with Windows 11 or Windows Server.

• Single to Multi-Session Compatibility: You can assign a machine to single users by using single session or use multi-session for scalability.

• RemoteApp: Offer full desktop or use RemoteApp to deliver individual apps.

• Scalability: Scalable and flexible environments could be created.



Subscription and Tenant

Q: What is subscription?

• A subscription is an agreement with Microsoft to use one or more Microsoft cloud platforms or services, for which charges accrue based on either a per-user license fee or on cloud-based resource consumption.

• Microsoft's Software as a Service (SaaS)-based cloud offerings (MS365 and Dynamics 365) charge per user license fees.

• Microsoft's Platform as a Service (PaaS) and Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) cloud offerings (Azure) charge based on cloud resource consumption.

What is a tenant?

• A tenant represents an organization in Azure AD.

• It is a dedicated Azure AD service instance that an organization receives and owns when it signs up for Microsoft Cloud services such as MS Intune, Microsoft Azure, D365, M365 etc.

• Each Active Directory tenant is different than the other tenant.

Requirement for Tenant Setup

• An Azure subscription on an active account.

• Azure Active Directory Tenant ID.

• Global administrator account within the Azure AD tenant.

Hostpool and Bastion

Hostpool: A hostpool is a collection of one or more identical virtual machines (session hosts) that delivers desktop and apps.

What is Bastion? 

Azure Bastion lets you connect to your virtual machine by using browser to seamless RDP to SSH without any need to expose them through public IP address.


Hybrid AVD Joined Deployment Steps

1. Create a resource group.

2. Under the resource group create a VNet.

3. Create a NAT Gateway with the Public IP and associate it with a VNet.

4. Create a standalone virtual machine using Windows Server operating system.

5. Start the standalone VM and connect to it.

6. Add ADDS role and promote it to DC.

7. Install Microsoft Entra Connect.

  • Installation to configuration.

  • Click Agree.

  • Set Express settings (use Express settings).

  • Connect to Microsoft Entra ID.

  • Username/Password of global admin.

  • Connect to ADS using Active Directory user account who is a member of domain admin & Enterprise admin.

  • Next -> Continue.

8. Create a hostpool.

9. Create a workspace.

10. Create VM using AD credentials.

11. Create users (AAD) once they are synced, assign RBAC roles (Desktop Virtualization User, Virtual Machine User Login).

12. Assign users to application assignment.
